JOE COOL

When it comes to hip-hop album covers, few designs are as instantly recognizable and iconic as the artwork for Snoop Dogg's "Doggystyle" album. And the man behind that unforgettable image? None other than Joe Cool, one of the most influential artists in the genre's history.

But Joe Cool's contributions to the world of hip-hop went far beyond just "Doggystyle." He continued to collaborate with Snoop on numerous other projects and album covers, and NFT's cementing his reputation as one of the most sought-after designers in the industry.
This is one of the first Death Row NFT's after Snoop Dogg acquired the rights to Death Row Records, the iconic West Coast rap label. Only 300

His influence on the genre is undeniable, and his work continues to inspire new generations of artists and fans alike.

Despite his immense success, Joe Cool remains a down-to-earth and dedicated artist, always striving to push the boundaries of his craft and create works that are truly unique and unforgettable. In the world of hip-hop, he is a true legend and a master of his craft.
Abstract Cool Joe #1 - Death Row NFT- Only 12 owners.
Turntable Terrorist - Death Row NFT - Only 3 owners
Thank you for visiting. If you enjoyed the music, don't forget to follow TrussOne on Twitter for more http://twitter.com/trussoner

Giant Worship - 1997 

"I made the screen print of “Giant Worship” in late 1997 when I was first learning how to use Adobe Illustrator. The hands are an illustration I cut out of  Rubylith with an X-acto knife. I then scanned the hands illustration and composed them in front of the icon face in a way I thought was successful. The frame and text were added in Illustrator. I was fascinated with the psychology behind worship, whether the deification was based in religion, rock stardom, celebrity, politics, or any other cult that promoted euphoric allegiance. Obviously, using a word like OBEY rather than “rejoice” or something else positive, gives a more cautionary and sinister slant to the image, especially when coupled with the ominous Icon Face and word GIANT. The idea was to discourage people from worshipping or obeying blindly. The print is full-bleed on marigold yellow paper because I was looking for a paper close in color to the mustard yellow I often printed as a background in my prints from that era. I bought the paper based on an online swatch, and when it arrived the yellow had a green cast I didn’t like. I used the paper for this print and one or two others, but the color always irritated me. I guess a silver lining is that I wanted my prints to be a bit irritating to people… and with this one I could empathize."

-Shepard Fairey

Edition size for this piece is 101.
